ving media ecology in spite of resource limitations and an inability to scale up. Based on six years of fieldwork in Hmong American communities in Wisconsin, Minnesota, and California, it analyzes the unique opportunities and challenges facing Hmong newspapers, radio, television, podcasts, YouTube, social media, and other emerging platforms. It argues that micro media industries, rather than being dismissed or trivialized, ought to be held up as models of media innovation that can counter the increasing power of mainstream media.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aHmong American mass media. 0aHmong Americans in mass media. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  amedia entrepreneurship, media outlets, niche, social media, media ecology, podcasts, Youtube, Instagram, mainstream media, social media influencers, influencer, LGBTQ, refugees, ehtnic media, race and media, activism, niche audience, Hmong, Hmong community, Asian American, Asian activism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2021 Englishz978311075418608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2021z9783110753967oZDB-23-DSL08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073913840uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/9781978823389?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781978823389423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781978823389/original  a978-3-11-073913-8  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-075400-1  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishb2021  a978-3-11-075418-6  